   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1819-12_page02.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="Id_where"/>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworth Town</placeName>
                  <date when="1819-12-24">
                     <choice>
                        <orig>Dec<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</orig>
                        <reg>December</reg>
                     </choice> 24<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1819</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>Dear Sir</persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>I have read <persName ref="./Personography.xml#TaylX2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Taylors</persName>
               <hi rend="underline">insertions</hi> &amp; <hi rend="underline">corrections</hi>
               <lb/>
               for <unclear>Perseverance</unclear> and the Lottery. I had not<lb/>
               time to read them all myself and I therefore<lb/>
               put them into the hands of a judicious<lb/>
               friend whose opinion is copied for you<lb/>
               in this letter -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I did not like what I read of these insertions<lb/>
               - I thought them of <unclear>flat</unclear>
               <del/>
               <add>
                  <unclear>spite &amp; unprofitable</unclear>
               </add>
               <lb/>
               but perhaps they may be useful to the<lb/>
               class of people for whom <unclear>might long for description</unclear>
               <lb/>
               them &amp; I would not <unclear>counteract</unclear> her <choice>
                  <orig>benevo<lb/>
               lent</orig>
                  <reg>benevolent</reg>
               </choice>
               <unclear>experience &amp;</unclear> - Let her try therefore &amp;<lb/>
               welcome. - &amp; tell her this in as civil a manner<lb/>
               as you can.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               But I request that you will, as my friend<lb/>
               advises, confine these inserted paragraphs<lb/>
               &amp; these <hi rend="underline">corrections</hi> to the edition of which<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#TaylX2">Miss Taylor</persName> disposes for her purposes <unclear>&amp; by</unclear> I beg<lb/>
               that you will not adopt these in <hi rend="underline">your</hi>
               <lb/>
               publications -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I have received only 3 clean sheets<lb/>
               from you and have not had any proofs<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1819-12_page03.jpg"/>
               These ten days. You can calculate how<lb/>
               much time it will take to <unclear>present</unclear> this<lb/>
               volume; but I should think that at the rate<lb/>
               you go on you will not have it finished<lb/>
               by Easter which I believe is the 4<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> of April<lb/>
               - I do not in the least mean to interfere<lb/>
               with your intentions but I request you<lb/>
               <del>know</del> will let me know whether I<lb/>
               understand them rightly. Do you intend<lb/>
               to publish these memoirs at Easter? -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I should also be glad to know, if<lb/>
               you have no objection to tell me <add>of</add> what<lb/>
               number your edition consists - I ask<lb/>
               this question that I may judge how often<lb/>
               the <del>engravings of</del> plates of some engravings<lb/>
               which I intend to beg <hi rend="underline">your</hi> acceptance<lb/>
               will require to be <unclear>retouched</unclear> for your<lb/>
               edition -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I beg you will send me by post "<hi rend="underline">
                  <unclear>Bingley's</unclear>
               </hi>
               <lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">useful knowledge</hi> under cover to A <unclear>Marquis</unclear>
               <lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Castle-Dublin_IE">Castle Dublin</placeName>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               If it is necessary that I should return<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#TaylX2">Miss Taylors</persName> interleaved book let me<lb/>
               know &amp; you shall have it -<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               I am <unclear>thus</unclear> Sir<lb/>
               your <choice>
                  <orig>obed<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>obedient</reg>
               </choice> Servant<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p>
                  <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1819-12_page04.jpg"/>
                  "In some places, she shows very bad <unclear>taste,</unclear> in<lb/>
                  "the ommissions she seems desirous to have made; Irony<lb/>
                  "&amp; <unclear>humor</unclear> she can by no means understand - &amp;<lb/>
                  "she seems to wish to avoid <unclear/> with great care, the<lb/>
                  "<choice>
                     <orig>
                        <unclear>encreasing</unclear>
                     </orig>
                     <reg>increasing</reg>
                  </choice> the geographical knowledge of her Norfolk<lb/>
                  "<unclear>readers</unclear> - or even giving them the trouble of <unclear>reading</unclear>
                  <lb/>
                  "words of three syllables - much good may her<lb/>
                  "alterations do them - I think they are not worth<lb/>
                  "talking about, but that the Editor should be confined<lb/>
                  "<hi rend="underline">absolutely to the <unclear>poor</unclear> of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Norfolk_ENK">Norfolk</placeName>
                  </hi> - &amp; - are quite<lb/>
                  "indignant at her <choice>
                     <orig>impertinance</orig>
                     <reg>impertinence</reg>
                  </choice> &amp; presumption &amp; <unclear/>
                  <lb/>
                  "she ought to write stories herself according to her<lb/>
                  "flat fancy"<lb/>
               </p>
               <p>
                  Put the letter to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GranX2">Miss Grant</persName> into 3<hi rend="superscript">d.</hi> Port &amp;<lb/>
                  Send the enclosed letter to Francis to<lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. L. Wilson's</persName> house who will take<lb/>
                  it with him to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Epping_ENK">
                     <unclear>Epping</unclear>
                  </placeName> where I suppose<lb/>
                  Francis now is<lb/>
               </p>
            </postscript>
            <closer>
               <address>
                  <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1819-12_page01.jpg"/>
                  <addrLine>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntW1">W. Hunter</persName> - Bookseller</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>
                     <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#St-Pauls-Churchyard_ENK">S<hi rend="superscript">t.</hi> Pauls Ch. Yard</placeName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>78:1:5%</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>- : 7 : 6</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>
                     <hi rend="underline">1 - 6 -</hi>
                  </addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>79:14:11%</addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>
                     <hi rend="underline">14</hi>
                     <hi rend="underline"/>
                  </addrLine>
                  <lb/>
                  <addrLine>65 <unclear/>
                  </addrLine>
                  <lb/>
               </address>
            </closer>
